'''Michael ("Mike") William Shields''' is a British [[computer scientist]].

==Overview==
Mike Shields has been an academic in the Department of Computing at the [[University of Surrey]] in [[Guildford]], southern [[England]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.computing.surrey.ac.uk/showstaff?M.Shields | title=Dr Mike W Shields | publisher=[[University of Surrey]] | location=UK | accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> His research contributions have been in [[theoretical computer science]], especially concerning [[Concurrency (computer science)|concurrency]]. In particular, he has written books on [[automata theory]]<ref name="mws1">{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=StJQAAAAMAAJ | title=An Introduction to Automata Theory | first=Michael W. | last=Shields | publisher=[[Blackwell Scientific Publications]] | year=1987 | isbn=978-0632017560 }}</ref> and the [[Semantics (computer science)|semantics]] of [[parallel computing]].<ref name="mws2">{{cite book|  url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MYxQAAAAMAAJ | title=Semantics of Parallelism: Non-interleaving representation of behaviour | first=Michael W. | last=Shields | publisher=[[Springer-Verlag|Springer]] | year=1997 | isbn=978-3540760597 }}</ref>

A meeting was held in 2006 at the [[British Computer Society]]'s offices in [[London]] to celebrate Shields' contribution to computer science (his "''innovative and elegant foundational work on models of concurrency''") on his retirement.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.surrey.ac.uk/computing/news/events/2006/models_of_concurrency_and_open_computing.htm | title=Models of Concurrency and Open Computing | publisher=[[University of Surrey]] |location=UK | date=24 November 2006 | accessdate=8 November 2012 }}</ref> He has since moved to [[Malta]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/mike-shields/11/b51/359| title=Mike Shields | publisher=[[LinkedIn]] | accessdate=7 November 2012 }}</ref>

==F. X. Reid==
'''F. X. Reid'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.linkedin.com/in/fxreid | title=FXReid | publisher=LinkedIn | accessdate=7 November 2012 }}</ref> (aka '''FXR''') is a [[pen name]] that Shields has sometimes used in his more humorous writings and even within his serious work.<ref name="mws1-fxr">{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=StJQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22F.+X.+Reid%22 | title=An Introduction to Automata Theory | first=M. W. | last=Shields | year=1987 | pages=2, 12, 209 }}</ref><ref name="mws2-fxr">{{cite book|  url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MYxQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22F.+X.+Reid%22 | title=Semantics of Parallelism: Non-interleaving representation of behaviour | first=M. W. | last=Shields | year=1997 | pages=38, 56 ,66 }}</ref>

Reid has been a long-time contributor to the [[British Computer Society]]'s [[BCS-FACS|FACS]] Specialist Group ''[[FACS FACTS]]'' newsletter in the past. For example, he has been an enthusiast for the [[COMEFROM]] statement and an expert on its semantics.<ref>{{cite article| first=F. X. | last=Reid | title=On the Formal Semantics of the COMEFROM Statement. | work=FACS FACTS | publisher=BCS-FACS |url=http://www.bcs.org/upload/pdf/facts200603.pdf | volume=Issue 2006-1 | pages=18–20 |date=March 2006 | accessdate=7 November 2012 }}</ref> Apparently reports of FXR's death in 2006<ref>{{cite article| first=Victor | last=Zemantics | title=Obituary: F.X. Reid |work=FACS FACTS | publisher=BCS-FACS |url=http://www.bcs.org/upload/pdf/facts200603.pdf | volume=Issue 2006-1 | pages=12–14 |date=March 2006 | accessdate=7 November 2012 }}</ref> were untrue, and his musings continued after this time in the newsletter.

F. X. Reid's most widely known work is "''The Song of Hakawatha'',"<ref>{{cite web | first=F. X. | last=Reid | url=http://www.cis.strath.ac.uk/~sinclair/hakawatha.html | title=The Song Of Hakawatha | publisher=[[University of Strathclyde]] | location=Scotland | year=1989 | accessdate=7 November 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050326032134/http://www.cis.strath.ac.uk/~sinclair/hakawatha.html | archivedate=26 March 2005 | df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUWsAAAAIAAJ&q=%22F.+X.+Reid%22 | title=Longfellow Redux | first=Christoph | last=Irmscher | publisher=[[University of Illinois Press]] | pages=123, 297 | year=2006 }}</ref> a [[parody]] of [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]]'s poem ''[[The Song of Hiawatha]]'' containing references to [[hack (technology slang)|hacking]], [[Unix]] and [[compiler]]s. F. X. Reid has also been mentioned in computer science books.<ref name="mws1" /><ref name="mws2" /><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uAEnAAAAMAAJ&q=%22F.+X.+Reid%22 | title=The Specification of Complex Systems | first1=Bernard | last1=Cohen | first2=William T. | last2=Harwood | first3=Melvyn I. | last3=Jackson | publisher=[[Addison-Wesley]] | year=1986 | isbn=978-0201144000 | page=26 }}</ref>

Reid has been quoted as saying ''In [[program proving]], only the presence of [[Software bug|bugs]] in one's proof is ascertainable, not their absence'',<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.freaknet.org/martin/tape/gos/crap/fxr | title=F. X. Reid — The Movie ? | website=www.freaknet.org | publisher=FreakNet Medialab | location=Catalonia | accessdate=7 November 2012 }}</ref> similar to but not the same as a well-known quotation by [[E. W. Dijkstra]] about [[software testing]].

